1
00:00:21,454 --> 00:00:24,252
[THUNDER CRASHING]

2
00:01:39,365 --> 00:01:41,663
Excuse me, preacher.

3
00:01:41,834 --> 00:01:43,995
I mean, for butting in.

4
00:01:44,170 --> 00:01:46,968
I didn't believe it down at the general store
when they said:

5
00:01:47,140 --> 00:01:48,607
"The preacher's up and left us."

6
00:01:48,775 --> 00:01:53,474
I says, "He wouldn't do nothing like that.
Just wait and see, he'll be back sure."

7
00:01:53,646 --> 00:01:55,944
But then I weren't sure.

8
00:01:57,583 --> 00:02:00,143
I know it didn't make sense
what we see'd and hear'd...

9
00:02:00,320 --> 00:02:03,778
...at the trial yesterday. No sense at all.

10
00:02:03,957 --> 00:02:07,324
But you leaving the church,
your place here, the people who need you...

11
00:02:07,493 --> 00:02:10,257
...that don't make no sense neither.

12
00:02:14,300 --> 00:02:17,269
I can understand the violence of a storm.
It's a natural thing.

13
00:02:17,437 --> 00:02:19,837
Not meant to harm anyone.

14
00:02:20,606 --> 00:02:22,369
But the violence of men...

15
00:02:22,542 --> 00:02:26,979
...their cruelty and savageness
to one another, to themselves...

16
00:02:27,146 --> 00:02:28,943
Please, you'll catch your death.

17
00:02:29,115 --> 00:02:32,573
That train ain't gonna be along for hours.
It hardly stops here these days.

18
00:02:32,752 --> 00:02:36,688
I'll flag it down for you when it comes.
Here, let me make us a fire.

19
00:02:38,958 --> 00:02:41,017
"Silver Gulch."

20
00:02:42,395 --> 00:02:44,989
I remember when I first came here.

21
00:02:45,164 --> 00:02:46,995
I was gonna strike it rich.

22
00:02:47,166 --> 00:02:50,260
A bonanza of souls to save.

23
00:02:51,637 --> 00:02:54,401
I will lead them into paths
they have not known.

24
00:02:54,574 --> 00:02:58,601
I will make the darkness light
before them...

25
00:02:58,778 --> 00:03:01,076
...and crooked things straight.

26
00:03:01,247 --> 00:03:04,842
When you get your steam up
you do some powerful preachifying.

27
00:03:06,586 --> 00:03:08,349
Yes.

28
00:03:09,555 --> 00:03:12,718
To a congregation of deaf ears.

29
00:03:13,292 --> 00:03:15,954
And the ones at the trial yesterday,
you heard it all.

30
00:03:16,129 --> 00:03:18,222
Christians.

31
00:03:18,398 --> 00:03:20,161
I just can't understand it.

32
00:03:20,333 --> 00:03:22,995
All that sinning, lusting and killing.

33
00:03:23,169 --> 00:03:25,694
And then swearing before the judge
on the Holy Bible...

34
00:03:25,872 --> 00:03:29,330
...to tell the whole truth,
and the way they...

35
00:03:29,509 --> 00:03:32,000
There must be some answer,
but I'm ignorant to explain it.

36
00:03:32,178 --> 00:03:35,409
- Not as ignorant as I am.
- Oh, no, preacher.

37
00:03:35,581 --> 00:03:38,607
You're educated, you're a man of God.

38
00:03:38,785 --> 00:03:40,753
He knows.

39
00:03:41,721 --> 00:03:44,246
He knows I've failed them.

40
00:03:45,391 --> 00:03:48,360
The shepherd
is running away from the wolves.

41
00:03:48,528 --> 00:03:50,723
Where do you aim to be going?

42
00:03:51,264 --> 00:03:53,061
I don't know.

43
00:03:54,600 --> 00:03:57,865
- I don't know.
MAN: How about going plumb to hell?

44
00:04:01,808 --> 00:04:06,142
A fellow can't sleep in peace
in this horse ball of a town.

45
00:04:07,246 --> 00:04:09,373
Oh, it's you.

46
00:04:09,549 --> 00:04:13,417
I didn't figure you'd have the guts
to show up around these parts again.

47
00:04:16,622 --> 00:04:19,648
I never forget a face, my good man.

48
00:04:19,826 --> 00:04:22,226
But I'm glad to make an exception
in your case.

49
00:04:22,395 --> 00:04:24,989
[DONKEY BRAYING]

50
00:04:26,032 --> 00:04:28,865
Heehaw up your tail,
you godforsaken jackass.

51
00:04:29,035 --> 00:04:32,835
Shut up, you.
This is a preacher standing here.

52
00:04:33,206 --> 00:04:34,969
Preacher?

53
00:04:35,141 --> 00:04:37,109
It can't be. He woke me up.

54
00:04:37,276 --> 00:04:39,744
They usually put me to sleep.

55
00:04:42,548 --> 00:04:43,913
Don't pay him no mind.

56
00:04:44,550 --> 00:04:46,313
PREACHER:
Who is he?

57
00:04:47,186 --> 00:04:50,986
PROSPECTOR: He's a con man.
A swindler. An old scalawag.

58
00:04:51,157 --> 00:04:53,717
How else can a man
live to be old nowadays?

59
00:04:53,893 --> 00:04:57,021
He come around here last year,
selling some kind of patent medicine.

60
00:04:57,196 --> 00:05:00,791
- Choctaw herbal elixir.
- Three people near died of it.

61
00:05:00,967 --> 00:05:03,060
He got out of town
just ahead of the tar and feathers.

62
00:05:03,236 --> 00:05:04,294
[LAUGHS]

63
00:05:04,470 --> 00:05:07,564
You can imagine my surprise this morning
when I realized where the devil I was.

64
00:05:07,740 --> 00:05:11,699
I just sold a dozen of my fully-guaranteed
miracle lightning rods...

65
00:05:11,878 --> 00:05:15,279
...when all of a sudden
it starts thundering and lightning...

66
00:05:15,448 --> 00:05:19,384
...like there was a heavenly inspector
testing the guarantees.

67
00:05:19,552 --> 00:05:20,849
You're lower than a rattler.

68
00:05:21,020 --> 00:05:24,615
Oh, come now, my cantankerous friend,
we're not so different, you and me.

69
00:05:24,790 --> 00:05:26,951
You know, I dig for silver too.

70
00:05:27,126 --> 00:05:29,560
Only in much softer ground.

71
00:05:29,729 --> 00:05:32,562
Though, I must say,
this town of yours has sure gone to pot.

72
00:05:32,732 --> 00:05:34,723
What's happened? The silver peter out?

73
00:05:35,234 --> 00:05:40,638
Sure sign when the whores and gamblers
start heading for the next sucker town.

74
00:05:42,041 --> 00:05:43,065
Good riddance.

75
00:05:46,078 --> 00:05:48,171
Preacher, huh?

76
00:05:53,619 --> 00:05:56,816
Nothing much left to preach about,
eh, Reverend?

77
00:05:56,989 --> 00:05:59,856
Oh, I forgot, you're leaving town too.

78
00:06:00,026 --> 00:06:03,189
Had a bellyful of religion, I take it.

79
00:06:06,165 --> 00:06:09,430
How about you and me teaming up?
We could make a hatful.

80
00:06:09,602 --> 00:06:13,698
You know,
with your face, my fingers...

81
00:06:16,609 --> 00:06:18,804
PROSPECTOR: Leave him be.
- Just said he had an honest face.

82
00:06:18,978 --> 00:06:20,036
What's wrong with that?

83
00:06:20,213 --> 00:06:22,579
He's as rotten as the three
at the trial yesterday.

84
00:06:22,748 --> 00:06:26,184
Trial? What trial?
Something happen around here?

85
00:06:26,352 --> 00:06:29,185
- A man was murdered.
- Just one?

86
00:06:29,355 --> 00:06:31,016
Slow day.

87
00:06:31,190 --> 00:06:32,953
You look green around the gills.

88
00:06:33,125 --> 00:06:36,492
What's the matter?
A little murder upset your tummy?

89
00:06:36,662 --> 00:06:38,994
It weren't the murder itself. It was...

90
00:06:39,165 --> 00:06:40,928
It's what?

91
00:06:41,334 --> 00:06:42,961
It was the way it happened.

92
00:06:43,135 --> 00:06:46,332
The things we hear'd at the trial.

93
00:06:46,906 --> 00:06:48,931
What did he have to do with it?

94
00:06:49,108 --> 00:06:53,044
- We was subpoenaed, the both of us.
- Yeah? Why?

95
00:06:53,212 --> 00:06:55,612
I was the one found the body.

96
00:06:55,781 --> 00:06:57,442
Where?

97
00:06:57,617 --> 00:06:59,608
In the woods.

98
00:07:03,589 --> 00:07:05,682
A few miles west of town.

99
00:07:05,891 --> 00:07:07,825
<i>Days like that...</i>

100
00:07:07,994 --> 00:07:13,990
<i>... when it gets too hot at the diggings,</i>
<i>I head for a ravine I know...</i>

101
00:07:14,166 --> 00:07:18,899
<i>... where I can soak a bit in a pool,</i>
<i>underneath the falls.</i>

102
00:07:19,071 --> 00:07:22,336
CON MAN:
<i>Never mind that. What about the body?</i>

103
00:07:22,508 --> 00:07:24,169
PROSPECTOR:
<i>I didn't see it.</i>

104
00:07:24,343 --> 00:07:27,710
<i>I mean, not right off.</i>

105
00:07:28,114 --> 00:07:29,672
<i>But...</i>

106
00:07:30,016 --> 00:07:31,779
<i>I don't know.</i>

107
00:07:32,251 --> 00:07:37,518
<i>There was something about the way</i>
<i>the air hung heavy all around...</i>

108
00:07:37,690 --> 00:07:41,524
<i>... even in the woods, that gave me...</i>

109
00:07:41,694 --> 00:07:46,597
<i>... a kind of nervous, prickly feeling.</i>

110
00:08:51,764 --> 00:08:53,459
Hello?

111
00:09:03,542 --> 00:09:05,203
Hello?

112
00:09:07,313 --> 00:09:08,871
Hello?

113
00:09:11,317 --> 00:09:12,978
Hello?

114
00:09:50,456 --> 00:09:52,321
[CON MAN LAUGHING]

115
00:09:54,226 --> 00:09:57,627
I know, I know. You know,
they always look so surprised...

116
00:09:57,797 --> 00:09:59,890
...them cadavers.

117
00:10:00,065 --> 00:10:03,694
I bet you, death must be a lot different
than anybody thinks.

118
00:10:03,869 --> 00:10:05,962
Well, go ahead, go ahead.

119
00:10:07,406 --> 00:10:10,034
Hm? Oh.

120
00:10:13,145 --> 00:10:15,943
I ran like all blazes.

121
00:10:20,653 --> 00:10:23,053
<i>Till I got back to town</i>
<i>and told the sheriff.</i>

122
00:10:54,954 --> 00:10:57,684
CON MAN:
How did you get mixed up in this, Rev?

123
00:10:57,857 --> 00:11:00,087
He saw them both on the road.

124
00:11:00,259 --> 00:11:01,920
CON MAN:
Both?

125
00:11:02,795 --> 00:11:06,196
Oh, you mean, there was a dame, huh?

126
00:11:06,999 --> 00:11:08,398
The murdered man's wife.

127
00:11:08,934 --> 00:11:13,371
<i>I passed them on the road,</i>
<i>early in the afternoon.</i>

128
00:11:15,641 --> 00:11:17,541
<i>Oh, God.</i>

129
00:11:18,043 --> 00:11:22,309
<i>We never know how close to us</i>
<i>death may be hovering.</i>

130
00:11:23,148 --> 00:11:24,843
<i>The sun was high...</i>

131
00:11:25,017 --> 00:11:29,181
<i>... pouring life and warmth</i>
<i>all over the face of the earth.</i>

132
00:11:29,355 --> 00:11:32,586
<i>And there they were,</i>
<i>coming down the road...</i>

133
00:11:32,758 --> 00:11:37,957
<i>... not knowing how soon, how very soon,</i>
<i>the road would end.</i>

134
00:11:42,334 --> 00:11:44,632
<i>There was something about them.</i>

135
00:11:45,504 --> 00:11:48,473
<i>The man looked so dignified,</i>
<i>so sensitive.</i>

136
00:11:48,641 --> 00:11:50,632
So alive.

137
00:11:50,809 --> 00:11:52,800
How was he killed?

138
00:11:53,279 --> 00:11:55,804
Stabbed with a dagger.

139
00:11:55,981 --> 00:11:58,882
You found the murder weapon too, huh?

140
00:11:59,051 --> 00:12:00,916
- Me?
- Yes.

141
00:12:01,086 --> 00:12:05,546
No, just one look at that face,
and I got out of there as fast as I could.

142
00:12:07,092 --> 00:12:09,890
Now, what makes people so jittery
about the dead?

143
00:12:10,062 --> 00:12:11,927
Why, some of my best friends
are corpses.

144
00:12:12,097 --> 00:12:13,792
The only ones you can trust.

145
00:12:13,966 --> 00:12:19,666
Oh, sure, they stink a little, but no more
than a few alive ones that I know.

146
00:12:19,838 --> 00:12:23,035
How'd the trial turn out?
They pin it on anybody?

147
00:12:23,208 --> 00:12:26,041
Well, there was somebody accused.

148
00:12:26,211 --> 00:12:30,875
There's always somebody accused.
Usually hanged. But was he guilty?

149
00:12:32,751 --> 00:12:34,912
It's Carrasco.

150
00:12:36,522 --> 00:12:38,490
Oh, Carrasco.

151
00:12:40,059 --> 00:12:44,223
Bless the Lord,
they got the right man for once.

152
00:12:44,396 --> 00:12:46,921
- I wonder.
- What?

153
00:12:47,099 --> 00:12:51,126
The bloodiest outlaw in this whole part
of the country, and you wonder?

154
00:12:51,303 --> 00:12:54,363
Why, if he was within 50 miles
of any crime, I'd convict him of it.

155
00:12:54,540 --> 00:12:57,771
- It's not quite so simple.
- Not quite so simple?

156
00:12:57,943 --> 00:13:00,275
It'd be simple enough
if it was me they caught.

157
00:13:00,446 --> 00:13:02,812
"Tar and feather him, boys."

158
00:13:02,982 --> 00:13:07,976
Sure, peddle a few lightning rods,
pick up a couple of bucks in a shell game...

159
00:13:08,153 --> 00:13:11,088
...fleece a yokel
without even scratching him...

160
00:13:11,256 --> 00:13:14,384
...and you're a scalawag.
Lower than a rattler.

161
00:13:14,560 --> 00:13:16,027
Yes, but do it in a big way...

162
00:13:16,195 --> 00:13:20,825
...kill, rustle, rob a train, clean out a bank,
bamboozle the government...

163
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:24,333
...and hocus-pocus, alakazam,
you're a public hero.

164
00:13:24,503 --> 00:13:27,063
They're writing dime novels
and singing songs about you.

165
00:13:27,239 --> 00:13:29,799
You're a somebody.
Somebody to reckon with.

166
00:13:29,975 --> 00:13:33,240
- And it's not quite so simple.
- You weren't there.

167
00:13:34,847 --> 00:13:35,871
You don't know.

168
00:13:36,048 --> 00:13:39,415
SHERIFF: A desperado wanted
in every territory he ever set foot on.

169
00:13:39,585 --> 00:13:40,779
Bloodthirsty vandal...

170
00:13:40,953 --> 00:13:43,888
...driven by a craving for our possessions
and our women.

171
00:13:44,056 --> 00:13:49,961
- Juan Carrasco, killer, robber, lecher...
JUDGE: The facts, sheriff.

172
00:13:50,696 --> 00:13:54,325
I'm sorry. I know we have to
prove our charges.

173
00:13:54,500 --> 00:13:57,560
In the eyes of the law,
a man is innocent until proven guilty...

174
00:13:57,736 --> 00:13:59,397
...and all that.

175
00:13:59,571 --> 00:14:03,735
Of course, we didn't get a chance to prove
our charges the last time we caught him...

176
00:14:03,909 --> 00:14:07,174
...because he burned down the jail
and escaped.

177
00:14:07,346 --> 00:14:09,746
Maybe we could give him 60 days
as a firebug.

178
00:14:09,915 --> 00:14:13,351
JUDGE: Just the facts, sheriff.
SHERIFF: The facts.

179
00:14:13,519 --> 00:14:16,750
Well, we know his past record.

180
00:14:16,922 --> 00:14:21,950
Trials, convictions, escapes, facts.

181
00:14:22,127 --> 00:14:24,891
Let's start by proving
his latest outrage wasn't beyond him.

182
00:14:25,064 --> 00:14:26,588
JUDGE:
Tell us about the capture.

183
00:14:28,801 --> 00:14:31,429
SHERIFF:
We'd been combing the countryside...

184
00:14:31,603 --> 00:14:33,434
...the biggest posse I could round up.

185
00:15:11,777 --> 00:15:13,972
Search down in there.

186
00:15:29,561 --> 00:15:30,892
Whoa.

187
00:16:09,234 --> 00:16:11,031
He didn't put up much of a fight.

188
00:16:11,203 --> 00:16:14,536
He got pretty cold feet
for such a hot country.

189
00:16:14,706 --> 00:16:18,301
He was all dirty, muddied up.
Must have been thrown by his horse.

190
00:16:18,477 --> 00:16:20,809
JUDGE: Did you find the dagger,
the murder weapon?

191
00:16:20,979 --> 00:16:23,004
No, it wasn't on him.
We searched everywhere.

192
00:16:23,182 --> 00:16:24,444
Phoo!

193
00:16:24,616 --> 00:16:26,447
[SPEAKS IN SPANISH]

194
00:16:27,286 --> 00:16:31,382
We going to listen all day
to this gringo bigmouth.

195
00:16:31,557 --> 00:16:34,822
Gonna tell us what a big hero he is, huh?

196
00:16:36,161 --> 00:16:40,461
All these gringos is big hero
with the <i>mexicanos.</i>

197
00:16:40,632 --> 00:16:42,793
Greaser, you call them.

198
00:16:42,968 --> 00:16:45,698
Kill the greaser,
they don't count like people.

199
00:16:45,871 --> 00:16:47,771
You don't even cut notch in the gun.

200
00:16:47,940 --> 00:16:51,740
- Come on, shoot. Everybody, shoot.
SHERIFF: Hold your fire.

201
00:16:51,910 --> 00:16:53,537
He's just trying to cheat the rope.

202
00:16:53,712 --> 00:16:56,977
<i>Sí,</i> the rope, she's more pretty, huh?

203
00:16:57,149 --> 00:16:58,878
JUDGE:
Put away your guns.

204
00:16:59,051 --> 00:17:02,111
It may not look like it,
but you are in a court of law.

205
00:17:02,287 --> 00:17:05,848
Justice doesn't need a courthouse
or trappings of any kind...

206
00:17:06,024 --> 00:17:08,925
...only order and truth.

207
00:17:09,094 --> 00:17:11,358
[SPEAKS IN SPANISH]

208
00:17:12,564 --> 00:17:14,759
Carrasco fall off the horse.

209
00:17:14,933 --> 00:17:18,198
Is no horse alive can throw Carrasco.

210
00:17:19,204 --> 00:17:21,365
<i>Enfermo,</i> I was sick.

211
00:17:24,910 --> 00:17:26,969
You want to know what happen?

212
00:17:27,145 --> 00:17:29,010
I tell you.

213
00:17:32,017 --> 00:17:33,644
He's good horse, that one.

214
00:17:34,519 --> 00:17:36,817
<i>He's strong, fast.</i>

215
00:17:37,756 --> 00:17:38,882
<i>I run him hard.</i>

216
00:18:29,641 --> 00:18:35,443
This water is bad or something.

217
00:18:35,614 --> 00:18:42,019
I ride more till my belly start to hurt bad,
my head.

218
00:19:03,575 --> 00:19:06,669
I don't feel pain like other man.

219
00:19:06,845 --> 00:19:07,869
But this...

220
00:19:22,561 --> 00:19:24,688
He capture me.

221
00:19:25,797 --> 00:19:27,788
Some day,
somebody going to pistol-whip you.

222
00:19:27,966 --> 00:19:30,833
Bluff and blowhard.
They hate to be taken with their boots on.

223
00:19:31,003 --> 00:19:33,096
JUDGE:
Are you guilty as accused?

224
00:19:38,010 --> 00:19:42,470
Look, I going to swing from the tree
if I say <i>sí,</i> if I say no.

225
00:19:44,082 --> 00:19:45,674
[SPEAKS IN SPANISH]

226
00:19:45,851 --> 00:19:49,810
You think the time has come for me
to pay for my crimes, huh?

227
00:19:49,988 --> 00:19:56,359
The ones I done, this ones you think I done,
this ones you afraid maybe I going to do.

228
00:19:57,295 --> 00:20:00,264
So why should I tell you lie, huh?

229
00:20:00,432 --> 00:20:04,732
<i>- Sí, presidente</i>, it was me who kill the man.
JUDGE: Why did you commit this murder?

230
00:20:04,903 --> 00:20:08,930
I do not murder, I kill him.
It's big <i>diferencia</i>.

231
00:20:14,746 --> 00:20:16,236
Why?

232
00:20:22,954 --> 00:20:25,582
Because of little breeze.

233
00:20:27,726 --> 00:20:30,251
[SPEAKS IN SPANISH]

234
00:20:31,663 --> 00:20:35,690
If not for this breeze,
this man would never be killed.

235
00:20:38,103 --> 00:20:41,504
<i>It was a hot time of day, like now...</i>

236
